With the dissolution of Countering Weapons of Mass Destruction
(CWMD), S&T will serve as the lead component in developing the
next generation of biological detection. CWMD’s biological detection
program, BioWatch, was plagued by prolonged event-to-detection
timelines, a limited suite of detectable pathogens, and high oper-
ating costs. As S&T works to develop potential replacements for
